# 05_resolver_translates — proof the listener translates long_name → abbrev.
#
# The DB at /com/curvz/app/data/widget_names.db has 386 rows; one of
# them is:
#
#   tb_nod    main_toolbar_node_tool_btn    src/Toolbar.cpp:786
#
# This script asks for `main_toolbar_node_tool_btn` — a long_name in
# the DB. The listener's resolver translates it to the abbrev `tb_nod`
# and looks `tb_nod` up in the registry.
#
# This is the "same script, two outcomes across the milestone
# boundary" test. The body never changed:
#
#   main_toolbar_node_tool_btn click
#
# Pre-s188 m1 (script-registry had only `tool.node`):
#
#   > main_toolbar_node_tool_btn click
#   error unknown object 'main_toolbar_node_tool_btn' (did you mean
#     'tool.node'?)
#
#   — the resolver translated to `tb_nod`, the registry didn't have
#     `tb_nod`, and the closest-name suggestion fell through to the
#     hand-picked `tool.node` entry.
#
# Post-s188 m1 (script-registry has `tb_nod`):
#
#   > main_toolbar_node_tool_btn click
#   (no error — the Node tool button clicks)
#
#   — the resolver translates to `tb_nod`, the registry has it, the
#     click dispatches. The user-visible toolbar reflects the change.
#
# Run this script post-migration and verify the Node tool turns on,
# the same way running `tb_nod click` would. This validates that the
# resolver is genuinely a translation layer — scripts can address
# widgets by their full GTK widget-name (read off `widget_names.db`
# or a Curvz log line) without needing to know the abbrev.

main_toolbar_node_tool_btn click
